15 SECTION 3.12.(e) G.S. 115C-431 reads as rewritten:
16 "§ 115C-431. Procedure for resolution of dispute between board of education the governing
17 body of a local school and a board of county commissioners.
18 (a) If the board of education governing body of a local school determines that the amount
19 of money appropriated to the local current expense fund, or the capital outlay fund, or both, by
20 the board of county commissioners to a local school administrative unit or charter school is not
21 sufficient to support a system of free public schools, then the chairman of the board of education
22 governing body of the local school and the chairman of the board of county commissioners shall
23 arrange a joint meeting of the two boards to be held within seven days after the day of the county
24 commissioners' decision on the school appropriations.
25 Prior to the joint meeting, the Senior Resident Superior Court Judge shall appoint a mediator
26 unless the boards agree to jointly select a mediator. The mediator shall preside at the joint meeting
27 and shall act as a neutral facilitator of disclosures of factual information, statements of positions
28 and contentions, and efforts to negotiate an agreement settling the boards' differences.
29 At the joint meeting, the entire school budget shall be considered carefully and judiciously,
30 and the two boards shall make a good-faith attempt to resolve the differences that have arisen
31 between them.
32 (b) If no agreement is reached at the joint meeting of the two boards, the mediator shall,
33 at the request of either board, commence a mediation immediately or within a reasonable period
34 of time. The mediation shall be held in accordance with rules and standards of conduct adopted
35 under Chapter 7A of the General Statutes governing mediated settlement conferences but
36 modified as appropriate and suitable to the resolution of the particular issues in disagreement.
37 Unless otherwise agreed upon by both boards, the following individuals shall constitute the
38 two working groups empowered to represent their respective boards during the mediation:
39 (1) The chair of each board or the chair's designee;designee.
40 (2) The superintendent of the local school administrative unit or the chairman of
41 the charter school board of directors, and the county manager manager, or
42 either's designee;any of their designees.
43 (3) The finance officer of each board; andboard.
44 (4) The attorney for each board.
45 Members of both the boards, their chairs, and representatives shall cooperate with and respond
46 to all reasonable requests of the mediator to participate in the mediation. Notwithstanding Article
47 33C of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes, the mediation proceedings involving the two working
48 groups shall be conducted in private. Evidence of statements made and conduct occurring in a
49 mediation are not subject to discovery and are inadmissible in any court action. However, no
50 evidence otherwise discoverable is inadmissible merely because it is presented or discussed in a
51 mediation. The mediator shall not be compelled to testify or produce evidence concerning
Page 26 DRH10571-MTa-148

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 statements made and conduct occurring in a mediation in any civil proceeding for any purpose,
2 except disciplinary hearings before the State Bar or any agency established to enforce standards
3 of conduct for mediators. Reports by members of either working group to their respective boards
4 shall be made in compliance with Article 33C of Chapter 143 of the General Statutes.
5 Unless both boards agree otherwise, or unless the boards have already resolved their dispute,
6 the mediation shall end no later than August 1. The mediator shall have the authority to determine
7 that an impasse exists and to discontinue the mediation. The mediation may continue beyond
8 August 1 provided both boards agree. If both boards agree to continue the mediation beyond
9 August 1, the board of county commissioners shall appropriate to the local school administrative
10 unit for deposit in the local current expense fund or to a charter school a sum of money sufficient
11 to equal the local contribution to this fund for the previous year.
12 If the working groups reach a proposed agreement, the terms and conditions must be
13 approved by each board. If no agreement is reached, the mediator shall announce that fact to the
14 chairs of both boards, the Senior Resident Superior Court Judge, and the public. The mediator
15 shall not disclose any other information about the mediation. The mediator shall not make any
16 recommendations or public statement of findings or conclusions.
17 The local board of education governing body of the local school and the board of county
18 commissioners shall share equally the mediator's compensation and expenses. The mediator's
19 compensation shall be determined according to rules adopted under Chapter 7A of the General
20 Statutes.
21 (b1) If agreement is not reached in mediation on the amount of money appropriated to the
22 local current expense fund, fund or charter school, and the amount to be appropriated has not
23 been calculated pursuant to this subsection for longer than the prior year, the sum to be
24 appropriated for the budget year in dispute shall be calculated as follows:
25 (1) The amount of moneys appropriated to the local current expense fund by the
26 board of county commissioners in the prior fiscal year that are expended in
27 that year by the local school administrative unit or transferred as required by
28 G.S. 115C-75.10, 115C-218.105, 115C-238.70, and 116-239.11 shall be
29 divided by the sum of the following: the average daily membership of the local
30 school administrative unit plus the share of the average daily membership of
31 any innovative, charter, regional, or laboratory school whose students reside
32 in the local school administrative unit for the prior school year. For charter
33 schools, the amount of moneys appropriated to the charter school in the prior
34 fiscal year that are expended in that year divided by the average daily
35 membership of the charter school.
36 (2) The amount from subdivision (1) of this subsection, rounded to the nearest
37 penny, shall then be multiplied by the sum of one plus the twelve month
38 percent change in the second quarter Employment Cost Index for elementary
39 and secondary school workers as reported by the Federal Bureau of Labor
40 Statistics.
41 (3) The amount from subdivision (2) of this subsection, rounded to the nearest
42 penny, shall then be multiplied by the sum of the following: the allotted
43 average daily membership for the school year plus the share of the average
44 daily membership of any innovative, charter, regional, or laboratory school
45 whose students reside in the local school administrative unit for the budget
46 year in dispute. For charter schools, the amount shall be multiplied by the
47 allotted average daily membership for the school year.
48 The board of county commissioners shall appropriate to the local current expense fund or the
49 charter school the sum from subdivision (3) of this subsection, rounded to the nearest penny, to
50 the local board of education for the budget year in dispute.
