2 SECTION 3.13.(c) Authorization of Bonds and Notes. – Subject to a favorable vote
3 of a majority of the qualified voters of the State who vote on the question of issuing bonds for
4 public school capital outlay projects in the election called and held as provided in this section,
5 the State Treasurer is hereby authorized, by and with the consent of the Council of State, to issue
6 and sell, at one time or from time to time, general obligation bonds of the State to be designated
7 "State of North Carolina Education Bonds," with any additional designations as may be
8 determined to indicate the issuance of bonds from time to time, or notes of the State as provided
9 in this section, in an aggregate principal amount not exceeding four billion dollars
10 ($4,000,000,000) for the purpose of providing funds, with any other available funds, for the
11 purposes authorized in this section. In determining whether this limit has been reached, the
12 issuance of a note or bond to pay an outstanding note is not considered an issuance.
13 SECTION 3.13.(d) Use of Education Bond and Note Proceeds. –
14 (1) Subject to the provisions of subdivision (2) of this subsection, four billion
15 dollars ($4,000,000,000) of the proceeds of education bonds and notes,
16 including premium thereon, if any, shall be used for the purpose of making
17 grants to counties for paying the cost of public school capital outlay projects,
18 repairs, and renovations. Proceeds of education bonds and notes shall be
19 distributed to public school units as if they were funds in the Needs-Based
20 Public School Capital Fund, except there shall be no matching requirements
21 imposed on the public school units.
22 Any additional monies that may be received by means of a grant or grants
23 from the United States of America or any agency or department thereof or
24 from any other source to aid in financing the cost of public school capital
25 outlay projects authorized by this section may be placed by the State Treasurer
26 in the Education Bonds Fund or in a separate account or fund and shall be
27 disbursed, to the extent permitted by the terms of the grant or grants, without
28 regard to limitations imposed by this section.
29 (2) The State Board of Education shall also require counties to report annually on
30 the impact of funds provided under this section on the property tax rate for
31 that year. These reports shall be public documents and shall be furnished to
32 any citizen upon request.
33 (3) The General Assembly encourages, in projects for which bond proceeds are
34 allocated, consideration by counties and local school administrative units of
35 projects that primarily involve materially improving the energy efficiency of
36 the school facility.
