17 SUPPORT FOR HIGH-POVERTY SCHOOLS
18 SECTION 5.3.(a) Article 13 of Chapter 115C of the General Statutes is amended by
19 adding a new section to read:
20 "§ 115C-209.2. Community schools support program.
21 (a) Program Established. – The Department of Public Instruction shall establish a
22 program (Program) to provide support to high-poverty schools that adopt a community school
23 model or other evidence-based models to address out-of-school barriers to learning.
24 (b) Definitions. – The following definitions shall apply in this section:
25 (1) Community school model. – The model following the Department of Public
26 Instruction's Whole School, Whole Community, Whole Child model based on
27 the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's guidance.
28 (2) Evidence-based model. – Any model established using evidence-based
29 methods that, in the discretion of the State Board of Education, achieve the
30 goals set in the Whole School, Whole Community, Whole Child model.
31 (c) Participation. – The Department of Public Instruction shall disseminate an application
32 form for participation in the Program for the following school year no later than June 1 of each
33 year. No later than July 1, any school that uses a community school model or other
34 evidence-based model to address out-of-school barriers to learning may apply to participate in
35 the Program. No later than August 1 of each school year that funds are made available for this
36 purpose, the Department of Public Instruction shall select geographically and culturally diverse
37 schools from among the applicants for that school year to participate in the Program. Priority
38 shall be given to schools that have high rates of student poverty.
39 (d) Implementation. – Each participating local school administrative unit shall hire one
40 full-time school-based coordinator per participating school. The school-based coordinator shall
41 assess local needs and assets and organize the integration of social, academic, and health supports
42 in coordination with school support personnel. The school-based coordinator shall also assess the
43 school's access to technical assistance and professional support to effectively plan and implement
44 the community school model or other evidence-based model. No later than July 15 of each school
45 year that a school participates in the Program, the school-based coordinator shall submit to the
46 Department of Public Instruction a request for funds for goods or services beneficial to meeting
47 the goals of the community school model or other evidence-based model for the following school
48 year. No later than August 15 of each school year, the Department of Public Instruction shall
49 evaluate each funding request and allocate funds as it deems necessary.
DRH10571-MTa-148 Page 39

