10 with the mission to increase the number of underrepresented, low-income, or first-generation
11 postsecondary degree or certificate students entering and completing their postsecondary
12 education at community colleges and universities. In furthering this mission, CAC operates an
13 innovative model of partnering with schools, communities, families, and postsecondary
14 institutions, including providing for a two-year service opportunity to recent college graduates
15 as near-peer college advisers working full time in the public schools, with an emphasis on
16 engaging college advisers who have similar backgrounds to the students the program seeks to
17 serve. Near-peer college advisers perform various services for those students that are key
18 components to the proven success of the program, including (i) attending postsecondary campus
19 visits, fairs, and workshops with students, (ii) assisting with registering for college entrance
20 exams, (iii) assisting with Free Application for Federal Student Aid (FAFSA) registrations and
21 completions, (iv) identifying available scholarships, (v) assisting with postsecondary
22 applications, and (vi) engaging with parents.
23 SECTION 7.3.(b) Funds for the Program. – Due to the effectiveness of the
24 innovative model operated by CAC and the potential for significantly impacting the highest-need
25 students as described in subsection (a) of this section, the sum of three million dollars
26 ($3,000,000) in recurring funds is appropriated from the General Fund to the Board of Governors
27 of The University of North Carolina for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to be provided to CAC for the
28 purpose of expanding the placement of college advisers in accordance with the requirements of
29 this section.
30 SECTION 7.3.(c) Use of Funds. – CAC shall focus the first two years of the
31 expansion of its program using the funds provided to it under this section by placing college
32 advisers in counties designated as tier one and tier two. For the third year of the expansion, CAC
33 shall use the funds provided to it to place college advisers in the remaining counties designated
34 as tier three in order to achieve placement of college advisers in all 100 counties of the State. In
35 addition, CAC shall select at least three additional postsecondary institutions to partner with in
36 order to increase the number of recent graduates working as near-peer college advisers to meet
37 the needs of the program expansion. Once CAC has reached the goal of placement of college
38 advisers in 100 counties, the funds provided to it for the program shall be used to continue the
39 mission of the program to increase access for North Carolina public school students to
40 postsecondary degree or certificate attainment at community colleges and universities.
41 SECTION 7.3.(d) Reporting Requirements. – CAC shall submit a report by June 1
42 of each year in which CAC spends State funds made available to it pursuant to this section to the
43 Joint Legislative Education Oversight Committee and the Fiscal Research Division on the
44 progress of expanding the placement of college advisers, data on the effectiveness of the program
45 in increasing access for students to postsecondary education, and the use of State funds.
46
47 CAREER DEVELOPMENT COORDINATORS
48 SECTION 7.4. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
49 Public Instruction the sum of one hundred thousand dollars ($100,000) in recurring funds for the
50 2026-2027 fiscal year for a Career and Postsecondary Planning Director position in the
51 Department's career and technical education division to focus on career planning in grades five
Page 46 DRH10571-MTa-148

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 through 12. There is also appropriated the sum of eighty-seven million dollars ($87,000,000) in
2 recurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year to increase the number of school-based career
3 development coordinators for grades six through 12.
4
5 FUNDS TO REMOVE BARRIERS FOR ECONOMICALLY DISADVANTAGED
6 STUDENTS TO PARTICIPATE IN THE CAREER AND COLLEGE PROMISE
7 TRANSFER PATHWAY PROGRAM
8 SECTION 7.5. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
9 Public Instruction the sum of five million dollars ($5,000,000) in recurring funds for the
10 2026-2027 fiscal year to fund additional costs for all economically disadvantaged students
11 enrolled in the Career and College Promise Transfer Pathway Program, including at least the full
12 costs of textbooks, transportation, meals on college campuses, fees, and technology. If these
13 funds are insufficient, the Department shall use additional unspent funds in the State Public
14 School Fund to fulfill this purpose.
15
16 PART VIII. MISCELLANEOUS
17
18 STATE BUDGET ACT APPLIES
19 SECTION 8.1. The provisions of the State Budget Act, Chapter 143C of the General
20 Statutes, are reenacted and shall remain in full force and effect and are incorporated in this act
21 by reference.
22
23 EFFECT OF HEADINGS
24 SECTION 8.2. The headings to the Parts, subparts, and sections of this act are a
25 convenience to the reader and are for reference only. The headings do not expand, limit, or define
26 the text of this act, except for effective dates referring to a Part or subpart.
27
28 SEVERABILITY CLAUSE
29 SECTION 8.3. If any section or provision of this act is declared unconstitutional or
30 invalid by the courts, it does not affect the validity of this act as a whole or any part other than
31 the part so declared to be unconstitutional or invalid.
32
33 EFFECTIVE DATE
34 SECTION 8.4. Except as otherwise provided, this act becomes effective July 1,
35 2026.
